<h2>Description of low vibration system</h2>

<p>The stringent requirements for <a
href="http://www.atm.ox.ac.uk/hirdls/home.htm">HIRDLS Test and
Calibration</a> necessitated the provision of a low vibration
equipment support inside the <a href="chamber_1.html">thermal vacuum
chamber</a>, one that could carry loads in excess of 500 kg with a
high centre of gravity.</p>

<CENTER><IMG SRC="mass_fig1.jpg"><BR> 
<BR><I>Fig 1: Three dimensional
drawing of the seismic mass on isolators and with the stanchions and
box-beam table attached)</I></CENTER>

<p>To achieve the specified low vibration environment the instrument
and its optical test equipment, the so-called <a
href="CMS_4.html">collimator-monochromator system (CMS)</a>, were
supported by a <strong>10,000 kg inertial mass</strong> resting on
four <strong>pneumatic isolators</strong>, Fig 1.</p>

<CENTER><IMG SRC="mass_fig2.jpg"><BR>
<BR><I>Fig 2: Photograph of box beam table</I></CENTER>
<BR>
<TABLE WIDTH=100%><TR><TD VALIGN=TOP>
<p>The simple box-beam
equipment support table shown in Fig 2 is connected to the mass via
two large diameter stanchions. The integrity of the vacuum enclosure
is maintained by Dacron-reinforced Viton rolling diaphragm seals, Fig
3.</p>
<p>The shape and weight of the reinforced concrete block ensures a low
centre of gravity even when the support table is loaded with test
equipment. The low natural frequency of the pneumatic mounts (3 Hz
vertical) and the high stiffness of the block (natural frequency > 100
Hz) ensure low, structure-borne vibration levels when making sensitive
optical measurements.</p>
</TD><TD>
</TD><TD>
<a href="mass_fig3_large.jpg"><IMG SRC="mass_fig3.jpg"></a><BR>
<BR><I>Fig 3: Diagram of sealing arrangement</I>
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<p>The success of the arangement, which included
supporting the instrument at an angle of 25 degress in the chamber
(see Fig 4) is borne out by the quality of the <a
href="CMS_4.html">field of view (FOV) plots</a> derived during test
and calibration. Other test equipment, such as the cold walls and
external <a href="targets_5.html">radiometric calibration targets</a>
were supported on heavy duty rails attached to the central section of
the chamber.</p>


<CENTER><IMG SRC="mass_fig4.jpg"><BR>
<BR><I>Fig 4: Photograph of HIRDLS in chamber</I></CENTER>
